You might catch a glimpse of our latest commercial during this year’s @lasvegasnfr featuring the incredible voice of my amigo Colter Wall. 

Colter’s rendition of Stan Jones’ classic “Cowpoke” is one of my favorite songs, so I picked a few lyrics that resonated and asked Colter if he could craft a new take on it by simply reading the lines and picking an original acoustic melody. 

It sounded great, so we paired visuals to create a spot that hopefully feels as true to life as the characters in it. They’re the real deal, and thanks to the good folks @cavenders for their trust to direct this spot and cast it with several friends who get out there and do it every day. 

These projects might look simple in their final iteration, but in reality there is an incredible crew of producers, artists and technicians who bring these things to life. My sincere thanks goes to the entire crew who worked on this; it’s one of my favorite projects of the year, and I hope y’all are as proud as I am of the final spot.

Jim Young, Lawty Cavalliere, and Dalley Phillips - all incredible cowboy names (not to mention great cowboys in their own right). This is likely my favorite working cowboy image I photographed in 2022; mostly because of the personal meaning behind it. The fact that we are closing a year that sounds as futuristic as 2022 (to my 43-year-old ears at least) and still have wild cowboys chasing wild cattle in the remaining vestiges of wilderness inspires me that all is not yet lost. Wild cow catchers are the epitome of what being an old time cowpuncher represents in my opinion…they generally work in the remotest areas of the West tracking and trailing wild beasts that often have never seen humans. They live in sub-par conditions and consider danger a novelty. I snapped this image while riding with Jim and his crew in Arizona this past spring. We had just returned from a grueling day, and the crew circled around to play a few hands of cards before bed. This was our course as we returned in the dark each night; only then to wake up a few hours later in the same darkness, saddle our mounts, and do it all over again.
Shootin the shit but outta ammo

I’m not much of a cow hand myself, but I’m fortunate to have spent some meaningful time with incredible cowboys across the West. Along the way, I’ve learned a few of the unwritten laws of big outfits. Some of the laws are universal while others change geographically from ranch to ranch. If you’re interested in reading a few of these range rules, I penned a story on the topic for the latest issue of Western Horseman magazine - “Code of the West.”

This is Milo Young, son of Jolyn Young and Wild Cowpuncher Jim Young. Jolyn has her hands full raising young Milo, as he tends to follow in his father’s ways. Milo, coupled with his sister Grace and brother Levi, make a loveable yet formidable trio for their mother. Notwithstanding, Jolyn navigates her life as a cowboy family’s mother and a cowboy’s wife. Those are likely the two titles in which she’s most proud; however, “author” is the title that directly affects us. 

Jolyn and her publisher, Trafalgar Books, have just released her emotional memoir documenting life on the range in contemporary America. 

“Never Burn Your Moving Boxes” is an inspiring story of a woman's strength and determination in the midst of a frontier lifestyle known to few. The book gives an intimate look into Jolyn’s life as a wife and mother living hours from civilization on some of America's largest cattle ranches. Peppered with humor and heartache, she paints a brutally honest picture of loneliness, alcoholism, family, love, and redemption. It's a narrative told from an unsung hero of the American West - the cowboy's wife. 

If you would like to read this incredible story, I hope you’ll take a look at the link in my bio and order a copy. I know I found it enlightening, and I’m sure you will too. - Bud

Sometimes I like a simple documentary film as much as any large project. This one is about my friend Jimbo Humphreys - a heckuva character and longtime cowboy. Jimbo just received the National Ranching Heritage Association’s annual “Working Cowboy Award,” and he’s as interesting as anyone I’ve ever met.
New arena cut for the WRCA and World Championship Ranch Rodeo sponsor Modelo Especial. The show starts today in Amarillo! @workingranchcowboyassoc

Craig Haythorn likely needs little introduction in the working cowboy world, but needless to say he was recently awarded the Golden Spur Award - one of the most prestigious national honors given in the ranching industry. The Haythorn story is one that should be told, and I hope this short documentary does justice to the legacy.

“Tender Mercies” is a film that was released 41 years ago starring Robert Duvall and Tess Harper. It didn’t do very well at the box office, but the movie ended up winning an Academy Award for best original screenplay and one for best actor. It’s evidently well known, but I just learned about the film a few months ago and it stuck with me as movies sometime do. The other day I was driving through Waxahachie where they shot it and found the old gas station/motel where the story takes place. If anyone has seen the film (or even cares), here’s a few phone photos I snapped of the farmhouse they turned into the set. I’ve also included a screenshot of what the set looked like when they made the movie. Hopefully anyone who has seen the film can get a little enjoyment out of these. It’s basically an early 80s drama about a washed up alcoholic singer in desolate rural Texas.
